{"key":"post-13272169","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13272169</id>\n<content>You want to make sure the grain spawn is &lt;i&gt;fully colonized&lt;/i&gt;, period.&amp;nbsp; Beyond that, there's no need to wait, but bear in mind, the very first 'fuzzies' on grain do not indicate full colonization.&amp;nbsp; Full colonization is when the grains are fully 'white'.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We use the term &lt;i&gt;consolidation&lt;/i&gt; with regards to fruiting substrates to give them time to actually digest part or most of the substrate before introducing to fruiting conditions.&amp;nbsp; Doing this with grain spawn is actually counter-productive because you want to use your spawn while the mycelium is still rapidly expanding.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I suspect the OPs problem is either contaminated grains or failure to properly pasteurize the bulk substrate material.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13275089</next>\n<prev>13271131</prev>\n<first>13267138</first>\n<last>13276926</last>\n<when>1285899029</when>\n<utime>10/01/10 05:10 AM</utime>\n</post>"}